00:35:47.060 --> 00:35:50.790
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: You might have
gotten something else entirely

00:35:50.790 --> 00:35:52.090
from the other book.

00:35:52.090 --> 00:35:53.390
I heard it's great.

00:35:53.390 --> 00:35:54.690
It's got four actors, you said?

00:35:54.690 --> 00:35:56.520
&gt;&gt; Dan Chaon: Yeah, it's
a really good audio book

00:35:56.520 --> 00:36:00.770
and there are some really
wonderful performances.

00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:02.800
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yeah, so that
has advantages the book does not.

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:04.100
&gt;&gt; Dan Chaon: Yeah.

00:36:04.100 --> 00:36:05.400
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Anything else?

00:36:05.400 --> 00:36:06.700
Is someone coming up here?

00:36:06.700 --> 00:36:09.000
Yes?

00:36:12.710 --> 00:36:19.450
&gt;&gt; Speaker: Hi, my question is
how can I be a good supporter

00:36:19.450 --> 00:36:22.180
of budding writers
in your household?

00:36:22.180 --> 00:36:24.930
So I have a 9-year-old
that's interested in writing

00:36:24.930 --> 00:36:26.630
and I have someone else

00:36:26.630 --> 00:36:28.000
in my household that's
interested in writing.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:29.910
So how can I be supportive?

00:36:29.910 --> 00:36:34.520
How can I be encouraging in that
regard, especially for a 9-year-old

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:38.080
and not be like helicopter mom?

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:39.380
&gt;&gt; Dan Chaon: Right.

00:36:39.380 --> 00:36:40.980
I think it's about reading.

00:36:40.980 --> 00:36:45.300
Absolutely, just making sure
that there are books in the house

00:36:45.300 --> 00:36:49.710
and making sure that they
have access to the library

00:36:49.710 --> 00:36:57.150
and I think creating a
space where there's --

00:36:57.150 --> 00:37:07.350
not to say cut out TV and video
games but also just create a space

00:37:07.350 --> 00:37:11.770
where there's time to do these
kind of more quiet activities and,

00:37:11.770 --> 00:37:14.630
you know, set aside time for that
I think it's really important.

00:37:14.630 --> 00:37:18.170 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Speaker: Right because we usually
have to come in his room at 1:00

00:37:18.170 --> 00:37:20.230
in the morning and say, "go
to bed" because he's reading.

00:37:20.230 --> 00:37:22.480
So I get that part, so we
just need to figure out how

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:23.830
to put those things on paper.

00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:25.130
Thank you.

00:37:25.130 --> 00:37:26.430
&gt;&gt; Dan Chaon: Absolutely.

00:37:26.430 --> 00:37:29.400
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I think
there was someone else.

